4 SECTION 4.9. Public Transportation Distribution and Use. – Mecklenburg County
5 must distribute sixty percent (60%) of the net proceeds of the tax levied under this Part to the
6 Authority. The Authority shall use the net proceeds distributed to it under this section only for
7 costs associated with financing, acquiring, constructing, operating, and maintaining any
8 combination of real and personal property for a public transportation system, specifically
9 including micro transit services. The Authority may accomplish these purposes by undertaking
10 these activities itself or by entering an interlocal agreement with a municipality in Mecklenburg
11 County that operates a public transportation system to use funds allocated under this section for
12 those purposes as directed by the Authority in the interlocal agreement. An interlocal agreement
13 entered under this section may include a binding commitment on the part of the Authority to
14 allocate all or a portion of these proceeds to the municipality for a defined number of years or
15 until a defined condition is met, such as the satisfaction of any debt that was issued for public
16 transportation systems. In addition, the Authority may enter an agreement with a private entity
17 whereby that entity uses these funds for this purpose as directed by the Authority in the
18 agreement. The net proceeds of a tax levied under this Part that are distributed to the Authority
19 may be included as revenues within the meaning of G.S. 159-81(4), including any modifications
20 of that statute. The following conditions apply to the use of funds distributed under this section:
21 (1) No more than two-thirds of these funds may be used for the capital and
22 operating costs of rail projects over any period of 30 calendar years combined.
23 Compliance with this section is first determined at the end of the first 30-year
24 period, and then annually thereafter based on the previous 30-year period.
25 Nothing in this section will be interpreted to adversely impact the rights of
26 bondholders to any funds distributed or pledged to secure bonds, notes, or
27 other obligations used to finance or refinance real and personal property for a
28 public transportation system.
29 (2) The Authority shall complete at least fifty percent (50%) of the Red Line as
30 evidenced by a scope of work schedule created and submitted by the general
31 contractor or construction manager on the project before the completion of
32 any other rail project, absent the existence or occurrence of force majeure
33 events that delay completion of the Red Line or make completion of the Red
34 Line impracticable. For the purposes of this section, a "scope of work
35 schedule" is defined as a listing of project tasks associated with a project time
36 line that is updated as the Red Line construction project progresses. For the
37 purposes of this section, force majeure events include fire, flood, earthquakes,
38 other elements of nature, acts of war, terrorism, riots, civil disorders,
39 rebellions or revolutions, nuclear or chemical contamination, epidemics,
40 quarantines, acts of the federal or State government, a declared state of
41 emergency, strikes or labor disruptions other than those specific to the
42 Authority, or other conditions beyond its reasonable control and which, by
43 reasonable diligence, the Authority is unable to prevent. Should a force
44 majeure event delay or halt the Red Line project, the Authority shall resume
45 the original Red Line schedule as soon as practicable when the force majeure
46 event has ceased or subsided. Planning, design, and construction work may
47 occur simultaneously on other rail projects, but only to the extent that those
48 activities do not interfere with or delay the completion of the Red Line.
49 (3) The Authority shall solicit input from the Towns of Cornelius, Davidson, and
50 Huntersville on all aspects of the Red Line design, including conceptual
House Bill 948-Third Edition Page 7

