35 PART V. METROPOLITAN PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION AUTHORITY
36 SECTION 5.1. Chapter 160A of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
37 Article to read:
38 "Article 34.
39 "Metropolitan Public Transportation Authority.
40 "§ 160A-900. Title.
41 This Article shall be known and may be cited as the "Metropolitan Public Transportation
42 Authority Act."
43 "§ 160A-901. Definitions.
44 As used in this Article, unless the context otherwise requires:
45 (1) Authority. – A metropolitan public transportation authority as defined by
46 subdivision (3) of this section.
47 (2) Board of trustees. – The governing board of the authority, in which the general
48 legislative powers of the authority are vested.
49 (3) Metropolitan public transportation authority. – A body corporate and politic
50 organized in accordance with the provisions of this Article for the purposes,
51 with the powers and subject to the restrictions hereinafter set forth.
Page 8 House Bill 948-Third Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Population. – The number of persons residing in respective areas as defined
2 and enumerated in the most recent decennial federal census.
3 (5) Public transportation system. – Defined in G.S. 105-506.1.
4 (6) Unit of local government. – Any county, city, town, or municipality of this
5 State, and any other political subdivision, public corporation, authority, or
6 district in this State, which is or may be authorized by law to acquire, establish,
7 construct, enlarge, improve, maintain, own, and operate public transportation
8 systems.
9 (7) Unit of local government's chief administrative official. – The county
10 manager, city manager, town manager, or other person by whatever title, in
11 whom the responsibility for the unit of local government's administrative
12 duties is vested.
13 "§ 160A-902. Definition of territorial jurisdiction of authority.
14 An authority may be created for any area of the State that, at the time of creation of the
15 authority, meets all of the following criteria:
16 (1) The area consists of a single county that has a population greater than one
17 million.
18 (2) The county borders another state.
19 (3) The county includes at least one unit of local government that operates a light
20 rail system.
21 "§ 160A-903. Creation of authority.
22 (a) The Board of Commissioners of a county for which an authority may be created as
23 defined in G.S. 160A-902 may by resolution signify its determination to organize an authority
24 under the provisions of this Article. The resolution shall be adopted after a public hearing thereon,
25 notice of which hearing shall be given by publication at least once, not less than 10 days prior to
26 the date fixed for such hearing, in a newspaper having a general circulation in the county. The
27 notice shall contain a brief statement of the substance of the proposed resolution, shall set forth
28 the proposed articles of incorporation of the authority, and shall state the time and place of the
29 public hearing to be held thereof. No county shall be required to make any other publication of
30 such resolution under the provisions of any other law.
31 (b) Each such resolution shall include articles of incorporation which shall set forth all of
32 the following:
33 (1) The name of the authority.
34 (2) A statement that the authority is organized under this Article.
35 (3) The name of the organizing county.
36 (4) A provision stating that an affirmative vote equal to at least seventy-five
37 percent (75%) of the membership of the board of trustees is required to amend
38 the articles of incorporation or to adopt or amend the bylaws of the authority.
39 (c) A certified copy of the resolutions signifying the determination to organize an
40 authority under the provisions of this Article shall be filed with the Secretary of State, together
41 with proof of publication of the notice of hearing on each of such resolutions. If the Secretary of
42 State finds that the resolution, including the articles of incorporation, conform to the provisions
43 of this Article and that the notices of hearing were properly published, the Secretary shall file the
44 resolutions and proofs of publication and shall issue a certificate of incorporation under the seal
45 of the State and shall record the same in an appropriate book of record. The issuance of a
46 certificate of incorporation by the Secretary of State constitutes the authority a public body and
47 body politic and corporate of the State of North Carolina. The certificate of incorporation is
48 conclusive evidence of the fact that the authority has been duly created and established under the
49 provisions of this Article.
House Bill 948-Third Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) When the authority has been duly organized and its officers elected as provided in
2 this Article, the secretary of the authority shall certify to the Secretary of State the names and
3 addresses of officers as well as the address of the principal office of the authority.
4 (e) The authority may become a Designated Recipient pursuant to the Urban Mass
5 Transportation Act of 1964, as amended.
6 "§ 160A-904. Territorial jurisdiction of the authority.
7 (a) The initial territorial jurisdiction of an authority created pursuant to this Article shall
8 be coterminous with the boundaries of the county that organized it.
9 (b) Except as provided by this Article, the jurisdiction of the authority may include all
10 local public passenger transportation operating within the territorial jurisdiction of the authority,
11 but the authority may not take over the operation of any existing public transportation without
12 the consent of the owner.
13 (c) The authority shall not have jurisdiction over public transportation subject to the
14 jurisdiction of and regulated by the Interstate Commerce Commission, nor shall it have
15 jurisdiction over intrastate public transportation classified as common carriers of passengers by
16 the North Carolina Utilities Commission.
17 "§ 160A-905. Membership; officers; compensation.
18 (a) The governing body of an authority is the board of trustees. The initial board of
19 trustees shall consist of 27 members, appointed as provided in this section. For each appointment
20 below, the appointing authority may appoint an alternate that may act in the absence of the
21 primary person appointed. The appointments are as follows:
22 (1) Six members appointed by the board of commissioners of the county that
23 created the authority. Of the members appointed by the board of
24 commissioners, at least one member must live in an unincorporated area of
25 the county and at least one member must have experience owning or operating
26 a small business. For purposes of this subdivision, a "small business" is one
27 that is independently owned and operated, not dominant in its field, and
28 employs fewer than 100 employees on a full-time basis.
29 (2) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
30 second largest population of residents that reside in the county.
31 (3) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
32 third largest population of residents that reside in the county.
33 (4) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
34 fourth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
35 (5) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
36 fifth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
37 (6) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
38 sixth largest population of residents that reside in the county.
39 (7) One member appointed by the governing body of the municipality that has the
40 seventh largest population of residents that reside in the county.
41 (8) Twelve members appointed by the governing body of the largest municipality
42 in the county that created the authority as follows:
43 a. At least three of these appointments must be made upon the
44 recommendation of an entity that represents business interests in the
45 county.
46 b. At least one of the remaining nine appointments by the governing body
47 must be an individual that has experience owning or operating a small
48 business as defined in subdivision (1) of this subsection.
49 (9) Two members appointed by the General Assembly, one upon the
50 recommendation of the President Pro Tempore of the Senate and one upon the
51 recommendation of the Speaker of the House of Representatives.
