16 entities.
17 (4) Legal and financial considerations with respect to human resources of a
18 transfer of assets, liabilities, and operations of the public transportation system
19 from the City of Charlotte or CATS to the Authority, including issues related
20 to, but not limited to, employee pensions, retirement plans, and benefits.
21 (5) A recommendation as to whether the transfer of assets, liabilities, and
22 operations of the existing public transportation system to the Authority is
23 feasible and advisable.
24 (6) Any other issue determined to be relevant by the Authority.
25 SECTION 6.3. Reserved.
26 SECTION 6.4. The Authority shall do the following no later than one year after
27 enactment of this act:
28 (1) Adopt bylaws that are consistent with the provisions of Article 34 of Chapter
29 160A of the General Statutes.
30 (2) Establish policies with respect to Board governance, including the adoption
31 of a Code of Ethics for Trustees and key employees and the adoption of a
32 Conflicts of Interest policy.
33 (3) Create a human resources plan. This includes, at a minimum:
34 a. Creating an organizational chart that specifies positions that report
35 directly to the Authority's Board of Trustees.
36 b. Completing the search for direct reports to the Board of Trustees.
37 c. Creating personnel policies and procedures, including those related to
38 employee recruitment and retention, compensation and benefit
39 policies and plans, and an employee code of conduct.
40 d. Taking all steps necessary to ensure participation by the Authority in
41 the Local Government Employees' Retirement System under Article 3
42 of Chapter 128 of the General Statutes.
43 e. Creating a plan, including a time line, to implement a transfer of
44 employees of CATS from the City of Charlotte to the Authority.
45 f. Developing or acquiring information technology and other assets
46 needed to implement the human resources plan.
47 (4) Develop financial policies for the Authority.
48 (5) Develop operational policies for the Authority, including policies related to
49 business continuity, system operation, maintenance of the system and system
50 assets, fares, purchasing and contracts, transit rules and regulations, travel
51 markets, transit service, and advertising and sponsorships.
